Ah, my thought was that we would actually be hiding real attributes, e.g. I suspected the following would prevent `B().d` from being accessed:

```Python
class A:
    d = 1

class B(A):
    def __getattr__(self, attr):
        if attr == 'e':
            return 2
        raise AttributeError(attr)
```

Turns out that proper attributes take precedence. I guess because otherwise you couldn't call `obj.__getattr__` at all.

